Sec. 90001. Border infrastructure and wall system.
Provides an additional $46.55 billion for U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) in FY 2025 to build, repair, and improve physical barriers, access roads, surveillance technology, and site preparation along the southwest border, with all funds available until September 30, 2029.

Sec. 90002. U.S. Customs and Border Protection personnel, fleet vehicles, and facilities.
Allots $4.1 billion for hiring and training new CBP agents and support staff through 2029, $2.05 billion in retention and performance bonuses, $855 million for vehicle acquisition and repair, and $5 billion for facility construction or leasing, while barring use of personnel funds for processing coordinators after October 31, 2028.

Sec. 90003. Detention capacity.
Allocates $45 billion to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) in FY 2025 for detention of single adults and family units, allowing family residential centers to hold aliens pending removal decisions and authorizing the Secretary of Homeland Security to set detention standards for adults.

Sec. 90004. Border security, technology, and screening.
Appropriates $6.168 billion for CBP in FY 2025 to procure AI-enabled inspection equipment, upgrade air and marine platforms, enhance surveillance along all borders, deploy biometric exit systems, screen unaccompanied alien children, combat drug trafficking, and commemorate border security efforts, while prohibiting funds for untested surveillance towers.

Sec. 90005. State and local assistance.
Provides $500 million for unmanned aircraft system detection, $625 million for 2026 FIFA World Cup security, $1 billion for 2028 Olympics security, and $450 million for Operation Stonegarden, plus $10 billion for the State Border Security Reinforcement Fund to reimburse states and localities for wall construction, ground preparation, crime interdiction, and alien relocation from small communities, with applications accepted within 90 days and a 1% administrative cap.

Sec. 90006. Presidential residence protection.
Sets aside $300 million in FY 2025 for reimbursing state and local law enforcement for extraordinary protection costs at non-federal properties designated for presidential protection under the Presidential Protection Assistance Act, provided the costs exceed normal operations, are directly tied to Secret Service requirements, and are certified by the Administrator of the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), with up to 3% of funds allocated for administration.

Sec. 90007. Department of Homeland Security appropriations for border support.
Provides an additional $10 billion to the Department of Homeland Security in FY 2025 for border-related mission activities, available until September 30, 2029.

Sec. 90101. FEHB improvements.
Establishes the FEHB Protection Act of 2025 to verify eligibility of family members added to federal health benefits plans, conduct audits of current enrollees, and mandate disenrollment of ineligible individuals, while allocating $66 million in FY 2026 for implementation through 2035.

Sec. 90102. Pandemic Response Accountability Committee.
Appropriates $88 million in FY 2026 for the Pandemic Response Accountability Committee to oversee coronavirus-related spending, expands the CARES Act definition to include this reconciliation act, and extends the oversight period through 2034.

Sec. 90103. Appropriation for the Office of Management and Budget.
Provides $100 million in FY 2025 to the Office of Management and Budget for budget and accounting efficiency initiatives across the executive branch, available until September 30, 2029. [end of text]


